---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Bermuda Itineraries — 3, 5 & 7 Days"
  description="Three opinionated Bermuda itineraries: a tight 3-day first visit, a comfortable 5-day trip, and a full 7-day island week. Logistics, what to skip, and honest timing."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/visit" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Visiting</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Itineraries</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Bermuda Itineraries</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Three opinionated plans: a tight 3-day first visit, a comfortable 5-day trip,
        and a full 7-day week that gets into the island's corners.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- Best time to visit callout -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-ocean-muted); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Best time to visit</h2>
        <div class="table-wrapper">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Season</th>
                <th>Months</th>
                <th>Verdict</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Spring</strong></td>
                <td>April–June</td>
                <td>Ideal. Warm, uncrowded, everything open. The clear choice for a first visit.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Summer</strong></td>
                <td>July–August</td>
                <td>Busy and hot (30°C / 86°F). Peak prices, peak crowds. Great if you want the full beach experience; less good for sightseeing.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Shoulder</strong></td>
                <td>September–October</td>
                <td>Excellent value, quieter beaches, warm water. Hurricane risk is real — purchase travel insurance and watch forecasts.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Winter</strong></td>
                <td>November–March</td>
                <td>Quiet. Some restaurants and beach bars close or reduce hours. Water too cool for most swimmers. Good for a low-key trip; not ideal for a beach holiday.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Logistics section -->
      <section style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Bermuda logistics — what you need to know before planning</h2>
        <p>
          Bermuda is not like other island destinations. The logistics matter and shape how you spend your days.
          The most important fact: <strong>tourists cannot rent cars.</strong> There are no car hire companies for visitors.
          Plan your itinerary around that constraint.
        </p>
        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Getting around</h3>
        <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <li>
            <strong>Bus + ferry pass ($62/week):</strong> The best value option for visitors staying five or more days.
            Covers all public bus routes and the Hamilton–Dockyard ferry. Slower than a taxi but covers almost
            every major attraction. Buy at the Hamilton Ferry Terminal.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Scooter (from ~$65/day):</strong> The flexibility choice. Lets you go at your own pace,
            stop where you want, and reach beaches that buses don't serve directly. Requires a valid driving licence.
            Keep left — Bermuda drives on the left.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Taxi ($60–85/hour):</strong> Comfortable and air-conditioned. Adds up quickly over a week.
            Best used for transfers, airport runs, and the odd evening when you don't want to wait for a bus.
            Taxis are metered; there are no ride-hailing apps in Bermuda.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Ferry (Hamilton–Dockyard route):</strong> Scenic and useful if you're heading to the Royal Naval
            Dockyard. Roughly 60–75 minutes, covered by the bus pass.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          Full transport guide: <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/getting-around">Getting Around Bermuda →</a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 3-Day Itinerary -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-14);">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-4); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="font-size: var(--text-base); padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);">3 Days</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">The First-Timer's Bermuda</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Three days is enough to get Bermuda right — if you don't try to do everything.
          This plan covers the two non-negotiables (the south shore beaches and St. George's),
          puts you in Hamilton for a proper dinner, and leaves room to breathe.
          It works best April–October.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 1 — Arrival and Hamilton</h3>
        <p>
          LF Wade International Airport sits on the east end of the island in Hamilton Parish.
          The taxi to Hamilton runs $30–40 and takes about 20 minutes. If your hotel is in
          Southampton or Warwick, budget $50–60.
        </p>
        <p>
          Check in, then take the afternoon at Horseshoe Bay Beach (Southampton) or Elbow Beach (Paget)
          depending on where you're staying. Horseshoe is the iconic shot — the pink sand, the turquoise
          curve of water. Go in the late afternoon when the light is good and the midday crowd has thinned.
        </p>
        <p>
          Dinner in Hamilton. Walk Front Street, have a drink at one of the harbour-facing spots,
          eat somewhere you'd eat at home — the restaurants on Reid Street and around Hamilton centre
          are the most consistent. See <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/eat">Where to Eat</a> for current recommendations.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 2 — Full Beach Day and Water</h3>
        <p>
          This is the day to commit to the south shore. Start at Horseshoe Bay, then walk the beach
          path east along the shoreline to Warwick Long Bay, Chaplin Bay, and Jobson's Cove. The walk
          takes 30–45 minutes depending on how often you stop. Bring water, reef-safe sunscreen
          (oxybenzone and octinoxate are banned on Bermuda beaches — enforce it), and your own snorkel
          if you have one.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the afternoon: rent a scooter and ride the South Shore Road. It's one of the best
          motorcycle roads in the world relative to its size — the Atlantic drops away on your left,
          the vegetation is subtropical, and the road is in good condition. Stop at any beach that
          catches your eye. Bermuda has no private beaches.
        </p>
        <p>
          Return to Hamilton for the evening. The Bermuda Rum Swizzle at the Swizzle Inn (Bailey's Bay,
          a slight detour) is a genuine local institution, not a tourist trap — worth the diversion
          if you're on a scooter.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 3 — St. George's and Departure</h3>
        <p>
          St. George's is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — the oldest continuously inhabited English
          settlement in the New World. It earns that designation. The town centre is compact, walkable,
          and genuinely old: the buildings, the streets, the layout. Walk King's Square, visit
          St. Peter's Church (founded 1612), walk the fortifications.
        </p>
        <p>
          From St. George's, it's a short taxi or scooter ride to <strong>Tobacco Bay</strong> for a
          final swim and snorkel in the sheltered, shallow bay. The rock formations here are distinctive
          and the fish activity is good even for casual snorkellers.
        </p>
        <p>
          Back to your hotel, collect luggage, taxi to LF Wade. Most US east coast flights depart
          early afternoon — check your departure time and plan backward.
        </p>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Transport for this itinerary:</strong> Taxis for arrival and departure.
            A single scooter day hire for Day 2. Bus for Day 3 (Route 1 or 3 to St. George's runs regularly from Hamilton).
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- 5-Day Itinerary -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-14);">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-4); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="font-size: var(--text-base); padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);">5 Days</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">The Comfortable Bermuda Week</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Five days is the right amount of time for a first visit if you want to actually see the island
          rather than sprint through it. The extra two days over the 3-day plan add the west end (Dockyard),
          a proper evening in Hamilton, and a night at a good restaurant.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Days 1–3</h3>
        <p>
          Follow the 3-day plan above. By the end of Day 3 you'll have covered the south shore, the east
          end, and Hamilton.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 4 — Royal Naval Dockyard and the West End</h3>
        <p>
          Take the ferry from Hamilton to the Royal Naval Dockyard — the 60-minute ride across the Great
          Sound is pleasant and the ferry is covered by the weekly bus pass. The Dockyard is Bermuda's
          most substantial cultural attraction beyond the beaches: the former British naval base has been
          repurposed into a working complex with the <strong>Bermuda Maritime Museum</strong>, craft studios,
          glassblowing workshops, and several decent restaurants.
        </p>
        <p>
          Book the <strong>glass-bottom boat tour</strong> from the Dockyard dock. Tours run most mornings
          and afternoons in season. The reef formations in the Great Sound and the wrecks in the shallower
          areas are visible even to non-divers. Bring underwater camera gear if you have it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Dockyard Craft Market (open seasonally, typically Tuesday–Sunday) is the best place on the
          island to buy something made in Bermuda rather than imported. Bermuda cedar woodwork, hand-painted
          glassware, and island-themed prints are the reliable finds.
        </p>
        <p>
          Return by ferry in the late afternoon. Dinner in Hamilton — this is the night for a good
          restaurant. See <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/eat">Where to Eat</a> for the current list of places that
          consistently justify their prices.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 5 — Slow Day and Departure</h3>
        <p>
          Leave Day 5 loose. Sleep late, revisit a beach that caught you, browse the Hamilton shops on
          Front Street, or do a second scooter run to any part of the island you didn't cover. The
          island is 21 square miles — there's no shame in revisiting a beach you liked.
        </p>
        <p>
          Early afternoon: taxi to LF Wade for your flight home.
        </p>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Transport for this itinerary:</strong> Weekly bus + ferry pass ($62) earns its cost here.
            One or two scooter day hires for flexibility. Taxis for airport transfers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- 7-Day Itinerary -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-14);">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-4); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="font-size: var(--text-base); padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);">7 Days</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">The Full Island Week</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Seven days lets you slow down and go deeper. This plan adds Bermuda's best underwater experience,
          the quiet mid-island parishes, the parts of St. George's most visitors miss, and one meal that
          justifies the flight. It's the right choice for repeat visitors and for anyone who wants to
          understand the island beyond its postcard version.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Days 1–5</h3>
        <p>
          Follow the 5-day plan above. By the end of Day 5 you've covered the south shore, St. George's,
          Hamilton, and the Dockyard.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 6 — The Underwater Island</h3>
        <p>
          Bermuda has more shipwrecks per square mile than almost anywhere on earth — the shallow reefs
          that made it a navigation hazard for centuries are now its most unusual attraction.
          This day goes underwater.
        </p>
        <p>
          Morning: <strong>Bermuda Underwater Exploration Institute (BUEI)</strong>, on the Hamilton harbour
          front. It's a genuine museum, not a tourist attraction in the pejorative sense — the
          permanent collection covers Bermuda's shipwreck history, deep-sea exploration, and the island's
          relationship with the ocean in an intelligent, well-curated way. Give it two hours.
        </p>
        <p>
          Afternoon: if you want to actually get in the water, return to <strong>Tobacco Bay</strong>
          for proper snorkelling. Rent gear at the bay (or bring your own). The rock formations and
          calm, shallow water make it the most accessible snorkelling on the island. For certified divers,
          several operators run reef and wreck dives out of Hamilton and the Dockyard — book in advance
          in peak season.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Day 7 — Mid-Island, a Beach, and One Good Dinner</h3>
        <p>
          The mid-island parishes — Devonshire, Smith's, Paget — are quieter Bermuda. This is where
          Bermudians live, away from the resort hotels and tourist infrastructure. Rent a scooter for
          the day and ride without a firm plan.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>John Smith's Bay</strong> (Devonshire) is the beach for today: a long, unhurried
          stretch of pink sand with no beach bar and no facilities. Bring your own supplies. This is
          where Bermudians go on their days off.
        </p>
        <p>
          Tonight is the night for the splurge dinner. <strong>The Reefs</strong> (Southampton) for
          the cliff-side setting and seafood, or <strong>Fourways Inn</strong> (Paget) for a more
          formal, historic-property dinner. Both require advance reservations and are priced at
          $80–120 per person. Neither disappoints at that price point.
          See <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/eat">Where to Eat</a> for full details and current booking guidance.
        </p>

        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Transport for this itinerary:</strong> Weekly bus + ferry pass for the first seven days.
            Scooter day hire on Days 2, 6, and 7. Taxi for airport transfers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Bottom links -->
      <section style="border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Plan the rest of your trip</h2>
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: var(--space-4);">
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/do" style="display: block; background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5); text-decoration: none; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Things to Do →</p>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin: 0;">Activities, tours, and experiences</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/eat" style="display: block; background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5); text-decoration: none; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Where to Eat →</p>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin: 0;">Hamilton restaurants and resort dining</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/stay" style="display: block; background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5); text-decoration: none; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Where to Stay →</p>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin: 0;">Hotels, cottages, and apartments</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/getting-around" style="display: block; background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5); text-decoration: none; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <p style="font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: var(--space-1);">Getting Around →</p>
            <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin: 0;">Bus, ferry, scooter, and taxi</p>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
